{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d8f7dee0-fe02-4eb3-8093-a3c52c244c56","content":"Here's the breakdown of all three breaking changes:\n\n---\n\n**1. SpanHelper.cs — Tighter ref-safety for collection-expression Spans**\n\n`[x * 2]` targeting `Span<int>` implicitly uses `stackalloc`. That memory is scoped to the loop body, so `results = items` creates a dangling reference after each iteration. C# 15 tightens ref-safety analysis to reject this.\n\n**Fix:** Accumulate into a `List<int>`:\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    var results = new List<int>();\n    foreach (var x in source)\n        results.Add(x * 2);\n    return results.ToArray();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. Metadata.cs — `this` is invalid inside `nameof` in attributes**\n\nC# 14 let `nameof` reference instance members in attribute arguments, but via the *unqualified* name — there's no instance at attribute evaluation time, so `this` is not valid. C# 15 enforces this strictly.\n\n**Fix:** Drop `this.`:\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. Pipeline.cs — `with` contextual keyword ambiguity in collection expressions**\n\n`with` is a contextual keyword (record `with { … }` expressions). Inside a collection expression `[with(x, y), z]`, C# 15 parsing now treats `with` as the keyword rather than a method call, creating a syntax error.\n\n**Fix:** Use the verbatim identifier `@with` to force identifier interpretation:\n```csharp\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n```\nOr rename the method to avoid clashing with the contextual keyword entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"217a7664-e5b5-4774-8a32-1350bb4ad2a0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 15 / .NET 11 breaking changes. These are hypothetical future versions (as of my knowledge cutoff). Let me think about what I actually know and what's plausible.\n\nWait - let me reconsider. The current date is May 2026. C# 14 shipped with 